04319nam a22006975i 9780812295504DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122955047 a10.9783/97808122955042doi  a(DE-B1597)521537  a(OCoLC)1052566888  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE302.6.L75b.G54 2018 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a974.9/030922231 aGigantino II, James J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWilliam Livingston's American Revolution /cJames J. Gigantino II. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHaney Foundation Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Making a Revolutionary, 1723–1774 -- tChapter 2. Reluctant Patriot, 1774–1776 -- tChapter 3. General to Governor, 1776–1777 -- tChapter 4. Defending the State, 1777–1778 -- tChapter 5. Fighting the War, 1779–1782 -- tChapter 6. Creating a New Nation, 1783–1789 -- tEpilogue -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWilliam Livingston's American Revolution explores how New Jersey's first governor experienced the American Revolution and managed a state government on the war's front lines. A wartime bureaucrat, Livingston played a pivotal role in a pivotal place, prosecuting the war on a daily basis for eight years. Such second-tier founding fathers as Livingston were the ones who actually administered the war and guided the day-to-day operations of revolutionary-era governments, serving as the principal conduits between the local wartime situation and the national demands placed on the states.In the first biography of Livingston published since the 1830s, James J. Gigantino's examination is as much about the position he filled as about the man himself. The reluctant patriot and his roles as governor, member of the Continental Congress, and delegate to the Constitutional Convention quickly became one, as Livingston's distinctive personality molded his office's status and reach. A tactful politician, successful lawyer, writer, satirist, political operative, gardener, soldier, and statesman, Livingston became the longest-serving patriot governor during a brutal war that he had not originally wanted to fight or believed could be won. Through Livingston's life, Gigantino examines the complex nature of the conflict and the choice to wage it, the wartime bureaucrats charged with administering it, the constant battle over loyalty on the home front, the limits of patriot governance under fire, and the ways in which wartime experiences affected the creation of the Constitution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGovernorszNew JerseyvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aAutobiography.  aBiography.  aBooks of Regional Interest.40uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229550440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812295504423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812295504.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK